# Sir Archibald Primrose, 1st Baronet, Lord Carrington (16 May 1616 – 27 November 1679) was a [Scottish](/Scotland) lawyer, judge, and [Cavalier](/Cavalier).  

![Portrait by [John Scougal](/John_Scougal), 1676](/File:John_Scougal_-_Sir_Archibald_Primrose.jpg "Portrait by John Scougal, 1676")  

He spent a career swinging between the pulpit of the [Privy Council](/Privy_Council_of_Scotland) and the bench of the [Court of Session](/Court_of_Session), leaving behind a trail of legal tomes, a few well‑placed titles, and a family tree that reads like a genealogical horror story.  

---  

## Early life  

Born the eldest son of [James Primrose](/James_Primrose_(Clerk_of_the_Privy_Council_of_Scotland)) (d. 1641), a writer and solicitor, by his second (or third—details are as fuzzy as a courtroom sketch), wife Catherine Lawson, daughter of Richard Lawson of Boghall, Archibald entered the world with a silver spoon and a stack of legal textbooks already under his arm.  

He inherited his father’s post as Clerk to the [Privy Council](/Privy_Council_of_Scotland) on 2 September 1641, a promotion that probably felt like being handed a freshly sharpened quill after years of doodling in the margins.  

---  

## Career  

### The Royalist interlude  

After the [Kilsyth](/Kilsyth) fiasco, he threw his lot in with [Montrose](/James_Graham,_1st_Marquess_of_Montrose), only to be captured at the disastrous [Philiphaugh](/Battle_of_Philiphaugh) on 13 September 1645. The Parliament of St. Andrews tried him for treason the following year; somehow, the [Marquess of Argyll](/Marquess_of_Argyll) managed to intercede and spare his neck, allowing him to walk out of the courtroom with his head still attached.  

His loyalty to the Crown earned him a knighthood from the beleaguered [Charles I](/Charles_I_of_England). He later followed the exiled heir, [Charles II](/Charles_II_of_England), and was created a [Baronet](/Baronet) of Carrington in 1651, a title bestowed during the march to the [Battle of Worcester](/Battle_of_Worcester).  

### The penal intermission  

His steadfast Royalist sympathies meant his estates were sequestrated and his debtors were legally barred from paying him—a financial penalty that would make any modern accountant weep. The [Act of Classes](/Act_of_Classes), a decree aimed at his person, was sealed on 10 March 1649, stripping him of his offices.  

When the Act was repealed, and after providing “satisfaction” to the Church (a phrase that probably meant he donated a few dusty manuscripts), he was reinstated as capable of holding office on 10 January 1651 and appointed Clerk to the [Committee of Estates](/Committee_of_Estates) on 6 June of that year.  

### The Restoration payoff  

During the [English Restoration](/English_Restoration), he received the plum appointment of [Lord Clerk Register](/Lord_Clerk_Register) via [Letters Patent](/Letters_Patent) dated 7 August 1660. A month later, on 14 February 1661, he was elevated to the [Lord of Session](/Court_of_Session) with the judicial handle “Lord Carrington.” Simultaneously, he snagged a seat on the [Lord of Exchequer](/Lord_of_Exchequer) and a spot on the [Privy Counsellor](/Privy_Council_of_Scotland) roster.  

His magnum opus was the [Rescissory Act 1661](/Rescissory_Act_1661), a legislative hammer that knocked the legs out from under [Presbyterianism](/Presbyterianism) until the 1690 Act resurrected it like a phoenix with a better PR team.  

### The inevitable fallout  

The [Duke of Lauderdale](/John_Maitland,_Duke_of_Lauderdale) eventually grew tired of his presence and forced Archibald to relinquish the [Lord of Exchequer](/Lord_of_Exchequer) and [Lord Clerk Register](/Lord_Clerk_Register) posts on 11 June 1676, swapping them for the far less lucrative role of [Lord Justice General](/Lord_Justice_General). He lost that too in 1678, a move that probably felt like being asked to leave the party early after the music stopped.  

---  

## Personal life  

Primrose’s love life was a revolving door of aristocratic alliances. His first marriage was to Elizabeth Keith, daughter of Sir James Keith of Benholme, and Margaret Lindsay. Together they produced a brood that could have filled a small regiment:  

* **Catherine Primrose** (d. c. 1677), who married [Sir David Carnegie, 1st Baronet](/Sir_David_Carnegie,_1st_Baronet) in 1663.  
* **Margaret Primrose** (d. 1690), who became the wife of Sir John Foulis, 1st Baronet, in 1661.  
* **Sir James Primrose** (1645 – c. 1671), who took a liking to the Sinclair family and married Elizabeth Sinclair, daughter of [Sir Robert Sinclair, 1st Baronet](/Sinclair_baronets).  
* **Maj‑Gen. Gilbert Primrose** (1649 – 1731), a Colonel in the [24th Foot](/24th_Foot) who probably enjoyed the occasional battlefield cigar.  
* **Sir William Primrose**, 2nd Baronet (1649 – 1687), who paired up with Mary Scott, daughter of Patrick Scott.  

After Elizabeth’s demise, Archibald married Agnes (née Gray) Dundas, a widow of Sir James Dundas of Newliston and daughter of Sir William Gray of Pittendrum. This union yielded two more children:  

* **Grizel Primrose** (1661 – 1723), who first tied the knot with Francis Sempill, 8th [Lord Sempill](/Lord_Sempill), and after his death, with Brig.-Gen. [Richard Cunningham](/Richard_Cunningham_(English_Army_officer))).  
* **[Archibald Primrose, 1st Earl of Rosebery](/Archibald_Primrose,_1st_Earl_of_Rosebery)** (1664 – 1723), who married Dorothea Cressy around 1690.  

He breathed his last in November 1679 and was interred in the [Dalmeny](/Dalmeny) church, where his and his father’s combined service to the Crown spanned roughly a century—give or take a few skipped generations. He was succeeded in the baronetcy by his eldest son, William, while his fourth son, the aforesaid Archibald, would later be created [Earl of Rosebery](/Earl_of_Rosebery) in 1703.  

---  

## Descendants  

Through his third son William, Archibald became a grandfather to [James Primrose, 1st Viscount of Primrose](/James_Primrose,_1st_Viscount_of_Primrose) (c. 1680 – 1706).  

Through his fourth son Archibald, the family line continued into the political stratosphere, eventually producing Prime Minister **[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery](/Archibald_Primrose,_5th_Earl_of_Rosebery)**.  

